@node Introduction
@chapter Introduction
@cindex introduction
@cindex overview

Pending is a standalone Emacs Lisp library for marking buffer regions
whose content will arrive asynchronously.  It provides a colored
placeholder where some asynchronously computed text is going to
appear, optionally with a spinner or progress bar, and atomically
replaces it with the result when ready.

@example
Calling Claude  @U{280B} [@U{2588}@U{2588}@U{2588}@U{2588}@U{2588}@U{2588}@U{2588}@U{2588}@U{00B7}@U{00B7}@U{00B7}@U{00B7}@U{00B7}@U{00B7}@U{00B7}@U{00B7}] 47%
@end example

Common use cases:

@itemize @bullet
@item LLM streaming responses (@code{gptel}, @code{agent-shell}, your
own Claude/OpenAI client).
@item Long-running shell commands run via @code{make-process}.
@item Network fetches via @code{url-retrieve}.
@item Arbitrary callback-driven asynchronous work.
@end itemize

@cindex why pending
The library aims for four properties that make asynchronous insertion
pleasant for end users:

@table @strong
@item Visible async
Users see immediately @emph{where} the answer will land and
@emph{that} something is happening.  No silent wait while staring at
a static buffer.

@item Atomic resolution
The swap from placeholder to result is exactly one undo step.  No
torn intermediate states, no partial-edit history pollution.

@item Edit-survival
While pending, the placeholder text is read-only.  Surrounding edits
adjust the placeholder's markers automatically; if the user deletes
the region outright, the placeholder cancels itself rather than
resolving into deleted space.

@item Backend-agnostic
The library does not commit to any particular async pattern; it
provides a small primitive (token + atomic swap) that integrates with
@code{gptel}, @code{make-process}, @code{url-retrieve}, plain timers,
or your own callback-driven pattern.
@end table

A single global animation timer drives all in-flight placeholders, so
spinning N concurrent regions costs only N overlay decorations per
tick, not N timers.


@node Installation
@chapter Installation
@cindex installation
@cindex requirements

Pending requires Emacs 27.1 or newer and has no third-party runtime
dependencies.

@section Via @code{package-vc-install}

@example
(package-vc-install
 '(pending :url "https://github.com/jwiegley/pending"))
@end example

To install from a local checkout:

@example
(package-vc-install-from-checkout "/path/to/pending" "pending")
@end example

@section Via @code{use-package}

@example
(use-package pending
  :vc (:url "https://github.com/jwiegley/pending")
  :commands (pending-make pending-region pending-insert
             pending-finish pending-cancel pending-list
             pending-demo)
  :config
  (global-pending-lighter-mode 1))
@end example

@section Manual

Drop @file{pending.el} somewhere on @code{load-path} and
@code{(require 'pending)}.


@node Quick start
@chapter Quick start
@cindex quick start

The simplest path is the positional API: mark a region or point as
pending, then atomically replace it when the answer arrives.

@section Mark a region for rewrite

@example
(let ((tok (pending-region (line-beginning-position)
                           (line-end-position)
                           "rewriting")))
  ;; @dots{} kick off async work @dots{}
  (pending-finish tok "the new text"))
@end example

@section Mark a single point for insertion

@example
(let ((tok (pending-insert (point) "Calling Claude")))
  (run-at-time 2 nil (lambda () (pending-finish tok "Hello!"))))
@end example

@section Cancel from point

Place the cursor on a placeholder and run @kbd{M-x
pending-cancel-at-point}.  The placeholder's overlay also binds
@kbd{RET} and @kbd{mouse-1} to the same command via
@code{pending-region-map}, so a single @kbd{RET} on the highlighted
region cancels the in-flight work.

@section Show the lighter mode

@example
M-x global-pending-lighter-mode
@end example

The mode-line gains a small @code{[N@U{23F3}~Ks]} summary while any
placeholders are active.  Clicking the lighter opens
@code{pending-list}.


@node Concepts
@chapter Concepts
@cindex concepts

@section Tokens
@cindex token
@cindex pending struct

Every constructor returns a @dfn{token} --- a @code{pending} struct
used as a handle for the placeholder.  Pass the token to
@code{pending-finish}, @code{pending-cancel}, @code{pending-update},
and friends to operate on the placeholder.

Tokens are valid until they reach a terminal state.  Operations on a
terminal token are no-ops with a @code{:debug} warning.

@cindex states, lifecycle
The lifecycle states are:

@table @code
@item :scheduled
The placeholder has been created but no work has begun (or the caller
has not yet sent any signal).

@item :running
The caller has indicated that work is in progress.  This state is
reserved for future use; current call-sites typically transition
directly from @code{:scheduled} to @code{:streaming} or to a terminal
state.

@item :streaming
At least one chunk has been delivered via
@code{pending-stream-insert}.  The end marker's insertion-type is
@code{t}, so subsequent chunks append at the end naturally.

@item :resolved
Terminal.  The placeholder's region has been replaced with the final
content.

@item :rejected
Terminal.  The placeholder failed; the region carries an error glyph
plus reason.

@item :cancelled
Terminal.  The user (or library) cancelled the placeholder; the
region carries a small cancelled glyph.

@item :expired
Terminal.  Reserved for future use.
@end table

@code{pending-active-p} returns non-nil for the first three states
(@code{:scheduled}, @code{:running}, @code{:streaming}); the others
are terminal.

@section The pending registry
@cindex registry
@cindex pending-alist

All active placeholders are recorded in a global registry.  Two
public functions surface it:

@table @code
@item pending-alist
Returns @code{((ID . STRUCT) @dots{})} for every registered
placeholder, including terminal ones still in transit.  Order is
unspecified; the alist is fresh and safe to mutate.

@item pending-list-active
Returns a list of structs in active states only.  Accepts optional
@code{BUFFER} and @code{GROUP} filters.
@end table

The registry is also the data source for @kbd{M-x pending-list} and
the mode-line lighter.

@section Lighter vs region highlight
@cindex lighter
@cindex highlight

The library distinguishes two visual treatments:

@table @strong
@item Region highlight
When the overlay covers existing buffer text (adopt mode
@code{pending-region BEG END STR} with @code{BEG < END}), the
overlay carries @code{pending-highlight} as its @code{face} property
so the user can see @emph{which} characters the asynchronous change
will rewrite.  In insert mode and zero-width adopt mode the overlay
has no face --- there is no pre-existing region to highlight.

@item Lighter
A small bold badge (face @code{pending-lighter}) attached to the
overlay's @code{before-string}.  This is the prominent visual marker
that draws the eye.
@end table

The simple API uses a static lighter (@code{:lighter} indicator).
The rich API can substitute an animated spinner, a determinate bar,
or an ETA bar in place of the static lighter.

The library NEVER applies a @code{face} text property to text it
inserts itself: labels, streamed chunks, and resolution / rejection
/ cancellation replacement text all land in the buffer as plain
text, so the surrounding font-lock and major-mode faces apply
normally.  Only the overlay (in adopt mode with a non-empty range)
and the overlay's @code{before-string} lighter /
@code{after-string} progress bar are faced.

@section Read-only protection
@cindex read-only
@cindex edit-survival

While a placeholder is active, its inserted text is read-only via
text properties:

@itemize @bullet
@item @code{read-only t}
@item @code{front-sticky '(read-only)} so insertions just before the
placeholder are blocked.
@item @code{rear-nonsticky '(read-only)} so insertions just after it
are allowed.
@end itemize

The user can edit before and after the placeholder freely, but not
the placeholder body itself.  The library binds
@code{inhibit-read-only} during its own operations so internal swaps
still work.

In adopt mode (@code{pending-make} with explicit @code{:start} and
@code{:end}), the library does @emph{not} retroactively add
read-only properties --- the caller owns that text.

@section Auto-cancellation paths
@cindex auto-cancellation
@cindex region-deleted
@cindex buffer-killed
@cindex timed-out

Several edge conditions auto-cancel an in-flight placeholder so it
cannot strand state:

@table @strong
@item Region deletion
If the user deletes the entire placeholder region, the overlay
collapses to zero length and a @code{modification-hook} cancels with
reason @code{:region-deleted}.

@item Buffer kill
@code{kill-buffer-hook} iterates the buffer's pending registry and
cancels each with reason @code{:buffer-killed}.

@item Deadline
When @code{pending-make} is called with @code{:deadline N}, a one-shot
timer fires @code{pending-reject} with reason @code{:timed-out} if
the placeholder is still active after N seconds.

@item Process death
@code{pending-attach-process} wraps the process sentinel; if the
process dies non-cleanly (or cleanly without an explicit resolve),
the placeholder is rejected with a reason derived from
@code{process-status}.

@item Emacs exit
When @code{pending-confirm-on-emacs-exit} is non-nil and active
placeholders exist, @code{kill-emacs-query-functions} prompts before
exit.
@end table


@node Simple API
@chapter Simple API
@cindex simple API
@cindex positional API

The simple positional API is the recommended starting point.  Each
function returns a token; pass that token to
@code{pending-finish}/@code{pending-cancel} when ready.

@deffn Function pending-region beg-or-token &optional end str
@findex pending-region
Two call shapes are supported.

@strong{Constructor:} @code{(pending-region BEG END STR)}.  Mark the
region @code{[BEG, END]} in the current buffer as pending an
asynchronous change.  When @code{BEG < END}, the overlay covers
existing buffer text and carries @code{pending-highlight} as its
@code{face} property so the user can see which characters the
asynchronous change will rewrite (the underlying buffer text is
untouched --- only the overlay carries a face).  STR shows as a
lighter badge at BEG via the overlay's @code{before-string}, faced
with @code{pending-lighter}.  If BEG equals END, the overlay carries
no face; only the lighter shows.  Returns a TOKEN (a
@code{pending} struct) usable with @code{pending-finish},
@code{pending-cancel}, and @code{pending-goto}.

@strong{Accessor:} @code{(pending-region TOKEN)}.  Back-compat
accessor: return the live overlay object owned by TOKEN, or nil.
Equivalent to @code{(pending-ov TOKEN)}.

@example
(let ((tok (pending-region (region-beginning) (region-end)
                           "summarising")))
  (gptel-request (buffer-substring (region-beginning) (region-end))
   :callback (lambda (text _) (pending-finish tok text))))
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-insert pos str
@findex pending-insert
Mark POS as pending insertion of asynchronously-computed text.  Shows
STR as a lighter badge at POS.  No region is highlighted (BEG = END).
Returns a token.  When eventually resolved with text via
@code{pending-finish}, the text is inserted at POS.

@example
(pending-insert (point) "fetching weather")
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-finish token text
@findex pending-finish
Atomically replace TOKEN's region with TEXT.  Transition to
@code{:resolved}.  Returns t on success, nil if TOKEN was already in
a terminal state.

The replacement happens inside an @code{atomic-change-group}, so undo
sees one step.  @code{inhibit-read-only} and
@code{inhibit-modification-hooks} are bound during the swap.  Side
effects: removes the overlay, clears markers, unregisters the token,
cancels any deadline timer, and runs the @code{:on-resolve} callback
once (errors there are caught and warned).

@example
(pending-finish tok "Hello, world!")
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-cancel p &optional reason
@findex pending-cancel
Cancel P, optionally with REASON (default @code{:cancelled-by-user}).
Calls P's @code{:on-cancel} callback @emph{first}, so the caller can
abort underlying work (e.g. kill a process).  Then transitions P to
@code{:cancelled} and replaces the region with a small cancelled
glyph (@samp{@U{2717} REASON}).  The inserted glyph is plain text
--- the library never adds a @code{face} property to text it inserts
itself; surrounding font-lock applies normally.

The @code{:on-cancel} callback is wrapped in @code{condition-case};
a buggy callback (or one that signals @code{quit}) does not break
the cancel pipeline.

@example
(pending-cancel tok)               ; cancelled-by-user
(pending-cancel tok :timed-out)    ; explicit reason
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Command pending-goto token
@findex pending-goto
Move point to TOKEN's start position.  Switches to TOKEN's buffer if
not already current.  Signals a @code{user-error} if the buffer is
dead.

Interactively, prompts via @code{completing-read} over the registered
placeholders.

@example
M-x pending-goto RET <pick from list> RET
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Command pending-list
@findex pending-list
Display all registered pending placeholders in a tabulated-list
buffer.  @xref{Interactive UI}, for the full description.
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-alist
@findex pending-alist
Return an alist snapshot @code{((ID . STRUCT) @dots{})} of all
currently registered pending placeholders.  Order is unspecified.
This is a fresh list; mutating it does not affect the registry.

@example
(length (pending-alist))                                 ; how many
(mapcar (lambda (cell) (pending-label (cdr cell)))       ; all labels
        (pending-alist))
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Command pending-cancel-at-point
@findex pending-cancel-at-point
Cancel the pending placeholder at point.  Signals a @code{user-error}
if no placeholder covers point.  Bound to @kbd{RET} and @kbd{mouse-1}
over a placeholder by @code{pending-region-map}.
@end deffn


@node Rich API
@chapter Rich API
@cindex rich API
@cindex pending-make

The rich keyword API provides full control: streaming, animation,
ETA bars, deadlines, and process attachment.

@deffn Function pending-make buffer &key label start end indicator @
deadline eta percent face spinner-style on-cancel on-resolve group
@findex pending-make
The full constructor.  Inserts (or adopts) a placeholder in BUFFER.
Returns the new @code{pending} struct.

Insertion modes:

@table @strong
@item Insert mode
If both START and END are nil, insert a new placeholder at point in
BUFFER.  The inserted label text is propertized read-only.

@item Adopt mode
If both START and END are non-nil (positions or markers), adopt the
existing region @code{[START, END]}; do not insert text.  Adopt mode
does NOT retroactively add read-only properties to the existing text;
the caller owns that text.
@end table

It is an error to supply only one of START or END.

@multitable @columnfractions .22 .78
@headitem Keyword @tab Meaning
@item @code{:label}
@tab Short string shown inside the placeholder.  Default
@samp{Pending}.

@item @code{:start} @code{:end}
@tab Adopt mode endpoints (positions or markers).  Both or neither.

@item @code{:indicator}
@tab @code{:spinner} (default), @code{:percent}, @code{:eta}, or
@code{:lighter} (static badge).

@item @code{:percent}
@tab Initial fraction in @code{[0.0, 1.0]} for @code{:percent} mode.

@item @code{:eta}
@tab Estimated total seconds for @code{:eta} mode.

@item @code{:deadline}
@tab Wall-clock seconds until auto-rejection with reason
@code{:timed-out}.

@item @code{:face}
@tab Override @code{pending-face} for the OVERLAY's @code{face}
property in adopt mode (BEG < END only).  Inserted text is never
faced by the library.

@item @code{:spinner-style}
@tab Key into @code{pending-spinner-styles}.

@item @code{:on-cancel}
@tab Function @code{(P)} called @emph{before} the cancellation
pipeline.  Abort underlying work here.

@item @code{:on-resolve}
@tab Function @code{(P)} called once on transition to any terminal
state.

@item @code{:group}
@tab Symbol for filtering via @code{pending-list-active}.
@end multitable

Side effects: inserts placeholder text (insert mode), creates and
adopts an overlay, registers the struct, optionally schedules the
deadline timer, and installs the buffer-kill hook locally.  Signals
@code{pending-error} on invalid arguments or a dead/read-only buffer.

@example
(pending-make (current-buffer)
              :label "Calling Claude"
              :indicator :spinner
              :on-cancel (lambda (_) (gptel-abort)))
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-update p &key label percent eta indicator
@findex pending-update
Mutate slots mid-flight without changing state.  Useful when the
caller learns more about progress --- e.g. switch from @code{:spinner}
to @code{:percent} once the total work size is known.

Clears the spinner-glyph render cache so any indicator/style changes
apply on the next tick.  No-op (with debug warning) if P is in a
terminal state.

@example
(pending-update tok :percent 0.42)
(pending-update tok :indicator :eta :eta 10.0)
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-stream-insert p chunk
@findex pending-stream-insert
Append CHUNK (a string) to P's region.  The spinner / progress
indicator stays visible.

On the first chunk (when P is @code{:scheduled} or @code{:running})
the loading-label content is deleted and replaced by CHUNK, the end
marker's insertion-type is flipped to t, and the status transitions
to @code{:streaming}.  Subsequent chunks append at the end marker,
which advances with the insert because of its insertion-type.

Streamed text gets the same read-only properties as the initial
label, but no @code{face} property: the library never faces text
it inserts itself, so the buffer's normal font-lock applies.  The
library binds @code{inhibit-read-only} and
@code{inhibit-modification-hooks} so its own inserts do not retrigger
the cancel-on-collapse hook.

This does NOT finalize.  The caller must follow up with
@code{pending-stream-finish}, @code{pending-reject}, or
@code{pending-cancel}.

If P is already terminal, this is a no-op (debug warning); the chunk
is dropped.  Signals @code{wrong-type-argument} if CHUNK is not a
string; an empty string is a no-op.

@example
(pending-stream-insert tok "Once upon a time, ")
(pending-stream-insert tok "in a faraway land@dots{}")
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-stream-finish p
@findex pending-stream-finish
Finalize a streamed placeholder.  Transitions P from
@code{:streaming} to @code{:resolved}.  Locks the end marker, strips
read-only properties from the streamed region (so the resolved text
becomes editable), removes the overlay's animated decorations,
deletes the overlay, unregisters P, and fires its @code{:on-resolve}
callback.

If P is @code{:scheduled} or @code{:running} (no chunks were ever
streamed), behaves like @code{(pending-finish P "")}.  If P is
already terminal, a no-op with debug warning.

@example
(pending-stream-finish tok)
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-reject p reason &optional replacement-text
@findex pending-reject
Mark P as failed with REASON and replace its region.  REASON should
be a string or a keyword/symbol describing the failure.
REPLACEMENT-TEXT defaults to a glyph plus the reason.  The inserted
text is plain --- the library never adds a @code{face} property to
text it inserts itself; surrounding font-lock applies normally.

Side effects mirror @code{pending-finish} (removes overlay, clears
markers, unregisters, cancels timer, runs @code{:on-resolve}).

@example
(pending-reject tok "API rate limit exceeded")
(pending-reject tok :network-down "Try again later.")
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-attach-process p process
@findex pending-attach-process
Wire PROCESS so its death rejects P appropriately.  The process's
existing sentinel, if any, is preserved: it runs first, then a
wrapper inspects @code{process-status} and calls @code{pending-reject}
on non-clean exit.  The reason is derived from the live process
status, which is robust against localized event strings.

Behaviour by status:

@table @code
@item exit @r{(code 0)}
If P is still active, reject with @samp{process exited without
resolving}.

@item exit @r{(non-zero)}
Reject with @samp{process: exited with code N}.

@item signal
Reject with @samp{process: killed (signal N)}.

@item failed
Reject with @samp{process: failed}.

@item closed
Reject with @samp{process: connection closed}.

@item run / open / stop / listen / connect
No-op; the placeholder remains active.
@end table

If multiple processes are attached over P's lifetime, the LAST
attach wins for the @code{attached-process} slot, but each prior
process's wrapper still chains through.  A stale process exit will
still flow into @code{pending-reject}, which is a no-op once P is
terminal because of the single-resolution guard.

@example
(let ((proc (start-process "build" nil "make")))
  (pending-attach-process tok proc))
@end example
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-active-p p
@findex pending-active-p
Return non-nil if P is in an active (non-terminal) lifecycle state.
The active states are @code{:scheduled}, @code{:running}, and
@code{:streaming}.
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-status p
@findex pending-status
Return P's current status keyword.
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-at &optional pos buffer
@findex pending-at
Return the pending struct at POS in BUFFER, or nil if none.  POS
defaults to point; BUFFER defaults to the current buffer.  Searches
the overlays at POS for one carrying a @code{pending} property.
@end deffn

@deffn Function pending-list-active &optional buffer group
@findex pending-list-active
Return the list of active pending structs.  Optional BUFFER and
GROUP filter the result.  Order within the result is unspecified.
@end deffn


@node Indicator modes
@chapter Indicator modes
@cindex indicator
@cindex spinner
@cindex progress bar
@cindex ETA

Choose a visual via the @code{:indicator} keyword to
@code{pending-make}.  The simple positional API always uses
@code{:lighter}; the rich API defaults to @code{:spinner}.

@multitable @columnfractions .15 .35 .50
@headitem Indicator @tab Visual @tab Use when
@item @code{:spinner}
@tab Animated glyph + label (default).
@tab Duration unknown but the library should look alive.

@item @code{:percent}
@tab Spinner glyph + bar + percent.
@tab Caller can supply a fraction in @code{[0.0, 1.0]}.

@item @code{:eta}
@tab Spinner glyph + bar + remaining-seconds estimate.
@tab Caller has a rough guess at total wall-clock seconds.

@item @code{:lighter}
@tab Static badge.  No animation.
@tab Visual marker only; no progress to convey.
@end multitable

@cindex piecewise asymptote
The @code{:eta} indicator uses a piecewise-asymptotic formula:

@itemize @bullet
@item @math{0 \le ratio \le 0.8} --- linear: fraction = ratio.
@item @math{0.8 < ratio \le 1.0} --- linear, slope 0.75: hits 0.95 at
ratio = 1.
@item @math{ratio > 1.0} --- asymptote: @math{1 - 0.05 e^{-(ratio-1)}}.
@end itemize

This avoids the ``100% but still working'' effect that bothers users.
The bar saturates toward (but never reaches) 100% past the deadline,
so callers can rely on ``not done until I say so.''

@cindex spinner styles
Spinner styles ship with: @code{dots-1}, @code{dots-2}, @code{line},
@code{arc}, @code{clock}.  Add your own:

@example
(add-to-list 'pending-spinner-styles
             '(my-style . ["a" "b" "c"]))
@end example


@node Integrations
@chapter Integrations
@cindex integrations
@cindex recipes

Each recipe below is a copy-pasteable function.  Adapt the prompts,
commands, and URLs to taste.

@section gptel --- streaming response
@cindex gptel

@example
(defun my/gptel-pending-stream (prompt)
  "Send PROMPT via gptel; stream the response into a pending placeholder."
  (let ((p (pending-make (current-buffer)
                         :label "Calling Claude"
                         :indicator :spinner
                         :on-cancel (lambda (_)
                                      (gptel-abort (current-buffer))))))
    (gptel-request
     prompt
     :stream t
     :position (pending-end p)
     :callback (lambda (chunk info)
                 (cond
                  ((stringp chunk) (pending-stream-insert p chunk))
                  ((plist-get info :error)
                   (pending-reject p (plist-get info :error)))
                  (t (pending-stream-finish p)))))
    p))
@end example

@section gptel --- non-streaming response

@example
(defun my/gptel-pending-call (prompt)
  "Send PROMPT via gptel; replace the pending placeholder with the response."
  (let ((p (pending-insert (point) "Calling Claude")))
    (gptel-request
     prompt
     :callback (lambda (response info)
                 (cond
                  ((stringp response) (pending-finish p response))
                  ((plist-get info :error)
                   (pending-reject p (plist-get info :error)))
                  (t (pending-cancel p)))))
    p))
@end example

@section @code{make-process} --- capture stdout
@cindex make-process

@example
(defun my/run-shell-pending (cmd)
  "Run CMD in a shell; stream stdout into a pending placeholder."
  (let* ((p (pending-make (current-buffer)
                          :label (format "Running: %s" cmd)
                          :indicator :spinner))
         (proc (make-process
                :name "shell-pending"
                :buffer nil
                :command (list shell-file-name "-c" cmd)
                :filter (lambda (_proc out)
                          (pending-stream-insert p out))
                :sentinel (lambda (_proc event)
                            (if (string-prefix-p "finished" event)
                                (pending-stream-finish p)
                              (pending-reject p (string-trim event)))))))
    (pending-attach-process p proc)
    (setf (pending-on-cancel p) (lambda (_) (delete-process proc)))
    p))
@end example

@section @code{url-retrieve} --- async fetch
@cindex url-retrieve

@example
(defun my/fetch-pending (url)
  "GET URL; replace the pending placeholder with its body."
  (let ((p (pending-make (current-buffer)
                         :label (format "Fetching %s" url)
                         :indicator :eta :eta 5.0
                         :deadline 60)))
    (url-retrieve
     url
     (lambda (status)
       (cond
        ((plist-get status :error)
         (pending-reject p (format "%S" (plist-get status :error))))
        (t
         (goto-char (point-min))
         (re-search-forward "^$" nil t)
         (pending-finish p (buffer-substring (point) (point-max)))))))
    p))
@end example

@section Pure-delay timer

A useful template for tests and demos:

@example
(defun my/delay-pending (seconds text)
  "Show a pending placeholder; replace with TEXT after SECONDS."
  (let ((p (pending-insert (point) (format "wait %ds" seconds))))
    (run-at-time seconds nil
                 (lambda ()
                   (when (pending-active-p p)
                     (pending-finish p text))))
    p))
@end example

@section Generic callback-driven async

@example
(defun my/with-pending (label callback)
  "Show a pending placeholder labelled LABEL.
CALLBACK is called with the token; it must arrange to call
`pending-finish' or `pending-reject' on the token."
  (let ((p (pending-make (current-buffer)
                         :label label
                         :indicator :spinner)))
    (funcall callback p)
    p))
@end example


